What's your excuse?</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uraedwulf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Raedwulf</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_thatch.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1208<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/2/02 5:23:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3442.topic&index=233>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Pledge to our flag, an ad for flag makers?</span><hr size=1> Gloriana:  Yep, it's my opinion.  As for the basis of it, I've read a boat load of Supreme Court decisions on the subject and was the top of my class (American Jurisprudence Award) in Constitutional Law - Individual Rights.  It's my opinion, based upon the cases and the actual words of the First Amendment quoted above, that the Pledge neither establishes a religion or prohibits the free exercise of religion (or non-religion).<br>
<br>
I'm not relying upon feelings, thoughts or opinion, just the words of the Amendment.  Your &quot;VALID argument&quot; claim is an unnecessary <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> ad hominem</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and a means to denegrate the other side.  Not kosher.<br>
<br>
I haven't observed an argument here (from you or anyone else) that demonstrates how hearing the Pledge read in school either a. Establishes a religion, or b. Limits the free exercise of religion.  Rather than attack my opinion, please simply provide an argument that the Pledge violates either prong of the clause.<br>
<br>
Point 1:  It is patently obvious that the extra-contextual writings of many of the drafters demonstrated that they weren't &quot;Christians&quot; which destroys the &quot;historic&quot; arguments of the Right.  I think you made that point quite well.  However, I'm not relying on that theory/argument and don't believe it says anything about the meaning behind the Amendment.<br>
<br>
Point 2:  The motivation of the Eisenhower administration also doesn't demonstrate that the Pledge either establishes religion or limits the free exercise thereof.  Their motivation was surely suspect, but I haven't empirically observed how the phrase itself violates the First Amendment.<br>
<br>
Point 3:  I think I must have missed your definition of the Establishment Clause.  If it was the separation of church and state argument, that's arguing outside the Amendment and inserting language that isn't there.  Jefferson may have wanted a brighter line (or wall), but that's not what he got.  The drafters appear to have believed that it was impossible to divorce religion from government (see other cites in thread regarding terms of Constitution), so prescribed the government from establishing a state religion (something most had fled in Europe) or interfering with an individuals free exercise of their own (another source of flight).<br>
<br>
Point 4:  Sure, you just quoted from CNN's quote of the 9th Circuit opinion, and they make an interesting argument (no matter the tortured route they made to even get to the question).  However, assuming that the Pledge sends the message claimed (which is not incontrovertible), that's still not establishing a religion.  Freedom <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> OF</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Religion, not Freedom <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> FROM</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Religion.  It's not forcing anyone to practice or believe a certain way.  The Pledge is not religious.  The mere mention of &quot;God&quot; is not religious.  Otherwise, Ozzy and Eddie Murphy are the world's most religious persons (ie. Gawd dammmit!)<br>
<br>
Juzu:  Please stop. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uglorianafrostglitter.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gloriana Frostglitter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1517<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/2/02 5:55:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3442.topic&index=234>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Pledge to our flag, an ad for flag makers?</span><hr size=1> Keeping this focused on the immediate issue:<br>
<br>
Public school teachers are state employees.<br>
<br>
Although students cannot be forced to participate in recitation of the pledge, the school district is nonetheless conveying a message of state endorsement of a religious belief when it requires public school teachers to recite, and lead the recitation of, the current form of the pledge.<br>
<br>
The Establishment Clause is the first amendment to the Bill of Rights and was intended to prohibit the federal government from declaring and financially supporting a national religion, such as existed in many other countries at the time of the nation's founding. <br>
<br>
1947: Everson v. Board of Education - all nine justices agree that the clause was intended to do far more than merely prohibit the establishment of a state religion. <br>
<br>
1952: Zorach v Clauson - the Court upheld the practice of giving public school students &quot;release time&quot; so that they could attend religious programs in churches in synagogues.  Writing for the Court in Zorach, Justice Douglas said the Constitution does not require &quot;callous indifference to religion.&quot; <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Note: prayer in school is fine, as long as it is not state instructor led/facilitated, implying state preference for one religion over another.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
1962: Engel v. Vitale - the Court ruled that New York's practice of beginning school days with a prayer drafted by school officials violated the Establishment Clause.  This is the case, the Court said, whether or not students are given the option of not participating in the prayer.  <br>
<br>
Following Engel, the Court has faced a whole series of prayer-related cases in the public school context raising issues such a prayer in special circumstances (e.g., graduation ceremonies), periods for silent meditation or silent prayer, and student-initiated prayer.  <br>
<br>
In general, the Court has demonstrated a willingness to strike down any practices that might be likely to be perceived either as coercive or as a state endorsement of religion.<br>
<br>
